\begin_layout Paragraph
Automatically detected beats
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To keep the transition model light we decided to modify 
\begin_inset Formula $1-P_{nn}$
\end_inset

 only at beat positions.
 Therefore the weighting function is set to 1 only at bar positions correspondin
g to beat positions, and zero elsewhere:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Theta(\phi_{k})=1_{d(\phi_{k},b_{k})=0}\label{eq:weight_detected}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When beats are automatically detected simultaneously to onsets we expect
 that the system is more flexible and do not need a closest-beat weighting
 scheme.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Observation Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The default hopsize of the predominant vocal detection 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{v}=0.0058$
\end_inset

 seconds, whereas the one used for computing the spectral flux feature in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "holzapfel2014tracking"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{s}=0.02$
\end_inset

 seconds.
 Increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{v}$
\end_inset

 deteriorated the note onset accuracy reasonably.
 Therefore in this work we used hopsize of 0.0058 seconds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bar Observation model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper for the bar position observation 
\family roman
\series medium
